	     Cape Town – Nine people died after a minibus taxi rolled on the N1 between Prince Albert and Leeu-Gamka in the Karoo on Friday, Western Cape Traffic Chief Kenny Africa said. "Apparently the driver of the taxi lost control of the vehicle," said Africa. ALSO READ: Kroonstad train crash: Condition of bodies causes uncertainty over death toll The crash occurred shortly after 05:00, and at that time three women and three men had died. A team of emergency workers, police and road traffic officials arrived to help, and the N1 was closed in both directions. ALSO READ: 18 injured in Durban taxi and bike crash Shortly before 07:00 another woman died, and over the next two hours, two of the injured men died. The injured occupants were taken to hospital for further treatment and the road was re-opened. Officials at scene of the taxi crash in the Karoo. (Supplied)   24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  